age = B01 | url = http://deseretnews.com/article/content/mobile/1,5620,700231011,00.html?printView=true | accessdate = August 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=policy>{{cite news | last = Barringer | first = Felicity | title = When the Bush Energy Policy Confronts Ancient Art | work = The New York Times | date = June 13, 2004 | url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F06E4D91330F930A25755C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all | accessdate = November 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=dust>{{cite journal | last = Kloor | first = Keith | date = January 25, 2008 | title = Dust Storm Rising Over Threat to Famed Rock Art in Utah | journal = [[Science (journal)|Science]] | publisher = [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] | volume = 319 | page = 394 | issn = 0036-8075 | url = http://ninemilecanyoncoalition.org/ninemilestudy.pdf | format = [[PDF]] | accessdate = July 25, 2008 | pmid=18218867 | issue = 5862 | doi = 10.1126/science.319.5862.394}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=nthp>{{cite web | title =  Nine Mile Canyon | year = 2004 | url = http://www.preservationnation.org/travel-and-sites/sites/mountains-plains-region/nine-mile-canyon.html | work = America's 11 Most Endangered Historic Places | publisher = National Trust for Historic Preservation | accessdate = May 8, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | last = McCourt | first = Tom | title = The Split Sky: A Journey of Discovery in Utah's Nine Mile Canyon | publisher = Southpaw Publications | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-0-9741568-1-1}} A memoir of a young man's experiences on a Nine Mile Canyon ranch in the 1960s.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Ninemile Canyon (Utah)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120209160436/http://www.castlecountry.com/what_to_see/Nine_Mile_Canyon.pdf ''Exploring Nine Mile Canyon''] ([[PDF]]), brochure with a map and guide (via [[Wayback Machine]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160425225424/http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/price/recreation/9mile.html Nine Mile Canyon - Know Before You Go] at BLM\n* [http://climb-utah.com/Misc/ninemile.htm Nine Mile Canyon Guide and Information]\n* [http://www.byways.org/explore/byways/15780 Ninemile Canyon Backway] at [[National Scenic Byway]]s Program\n* [http://9mcc.org Nine Mile Canyon Coalition], a group dedicated to the preservation of Ninemile Canyon\n* [http://www.preservationnation.org/take-action/advocacy-center/action-alerts/nine-mile-canyon-at-risk.html Action Alert from the National Trust for Historic Preservation]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n\n[[Category:Native American history of Utah]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Utah]]\n[[Category:Fremont culture]]\n[[Category:Rock art in North America]]\n[[Category:Canyons and gorges of Utah]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Carbon County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Duchesne County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Bureau of Land Management areas in Utah]]\n[[Category:Petroglyphs in Utah]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places Multiple Property Submissions]]\n", "name_user": "An Errant Knight", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ninemile_Canyon_(Utah)"}
{"title_page": "Rainbow (1978 film)", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Rainbow\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = Biography<br>Drama<br>Music\n| based_on             = ''Rainbow: The Stormy Life of Judy Garland'' by Christopher Finch\n| writer               = [[John McGreevey]]\n| director             = [[Jackie Cooper]]\n| starring             = [[Andrea McArdle]]<br>[[Don Murray (actor)|Don Murray]]<br>[[Michael Parks]]<br>[[Piper Laurie]]<br>[[Rue McClanahan]]\n| music                = [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| executive_producer   = Greg Strangis<br>[[William Hogan (author)|William Hogan]]\n| producer             = Peter Dunne\n| editor               = Jerry Dronsky\n| cinematography       = Howard Schwartz\n| location             = \n| runtime              = 97 minutes\n| company              = Ten-Four Productions\n| distributor          = [[NBC]]\n| network              = NBC\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1978|11|06}}\n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Rainbow''''' is a 1978 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[biographical film|biographical]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] which chronicles the early years of singer-actress [[Judy Garland]], portrayed by [[Andrea McArdle]]. Directed by [[Jackie Cooper]], it was written by [[John McGreevey]] based on the 1975 book ''Rainbow: The Stormy Life of Judy Garland'' by Christopher Finch. It originally aired on ''[[The NBC Monday Movie|NBC Monday Night at the Movies]]'' on November 6, 1978. The casting of McArdle as Judy Garland was heavily criticized at the time, as the actress did not resemble nor sound remotely like Garland.\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe early life and struggles of Judy Garland during her early years in [[vaudeville]], and follows her through her illustrious and highly-publicized rise to stardom at [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] studios; her trials as a youngster in dealing with the movie studio system that held her back while her mother was forever pushing her to excel, as well as all the backstage joy and heartbreak during the filming of ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' (1939).\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Andrea McArdle]] as [[Judy Garland]]\n*[[Don Murray (actor)|Don Murray]] as Frank Gumm\n*[[Michael Parks]] as [[Roger Edens]]\n*[[Piper Laurie]] as Ethel Gumm\n*[[Rue McClanahan]] as [[Ida Koverman]]\n*[[Jack Carter (comedian)|Jack Carter]] as [[George Jessel (actor)|George Jessel]]\n*[[Nicholas Pryor]] as Bill Gilmore\n*[[Donna Pescow]] as Jimmie Gumm\n*[[Martin Balsam]] as [[Louis B. Mayer]]\n*[[Johnny Doran (actor)|Johnny Doran]] as [[Jackie Cooper]]\n\n==Award==\n'''[[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]'''\n* 1979: [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Limited Series or Movie|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Limited Series or a Special]] \u2013 Howard Schwartz\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=0078136|title=Rainbow}}\n*{{tcmdb title|20167|Rainbow}}\n\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Judy Garland]]\n[[Category:1978 television films]]\n[[Category:1970s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:1970s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American musical drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Biographical television films]]\n[[Category:NBC network original films]]\n[[Category:Films based on biographies]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1920s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1930s]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about singers]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jackie Cooper]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Rainbow\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = Biography<br>Drama<br>Music\n| based_on             = ''Rainbow: The Stormy Life of Judy Garland'' by Christopher Finch\n| writer               = [[John McGreevey]]\n| director             = [[Jackie Cooper]]\n| starring             = [[Andrea McArdle]]<br>[[Don Murray (actor)|Don Murray]]<br>[[Michael Parks]]<br>[[Piper Laurie]]<br>[[Rue McClanahan]]\n| music                = [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| executive_producer   = Greg Strangis<br>[[William Hogan (author)|William Hogan]]\n| producer             = Peter Dunne\n| editor               = Jerry Dronsky\n| cinematography       = Howard Schwartz\n| location             = \n| runtime              = 97 minutes\n| company              = Ten-Four Productions\n| distributor          = [[NBC]]\n| network              = NBC\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1978|11|06}}\n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Rainbow''''' is a 1978 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[biographical film|biographical]] [[musical film|musical drama film]] which chronicles the early years of singer-actress [[Judy Garland]], portrayed by [[Andrea McArdle]]. Directed by [[Jackie Cooper]], it was written by [[John McGreevey]] based on the 1975 book ''Rainbow: The Stormy Life of Judy Garland'' by Christopher Finch. It originally aired on ''[[The NBC Monday Movie|NBC Monday Night at the Movies]]'' on November 6, 1978. The casting of McArdle as Judy Garland was heavily criticized at the time, as the actress did not resemble nor sound remotely like Garland.\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe early life and struggles of Judy Garland during her early years in [[vaudeville]], and follows her through her illustrious and highly-publicized rise to stardom at [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] studios; her trials as a youngster in dealing with the movie studio system that held her back while her mother was forever pushing her to excel, as well as all the backstage joy and heartbreak during the filming of ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' (1939).\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Andrea McArdle]] as [[Judy Garland]]\n*[[Don Murray (actor)|Don Murray]] as Frank Gumm\n*[[Michael Parks]] as [[Roger Edens]]\n*[[Piper Laurie]] as Ethel Gumm\n*[[Rue McClanahan]] as [[Ida Koverman]]\n*[[Jack Carter (comedian)|Jack Carter]] as [[George Jessel (actor)|George Jessel]]\n*[[Nicholas Pryor]] as Bill Gilmore\n*[[Donna Pescow]] as Jimmie Gumm\n*[[Martin Balsam]] as [[Louis B. Mayer]]\n*[[Johnny Doran (actor)|Johnny Doran]] as [[Jackie Cooper]]\n\n==Award==\n'''[[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]'''\n* 1979: [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Limited Series or Movie|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Limited Series or a Special]] \u2013 Howard Schwartz\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=0078136|title=Rainbow}}\n*{{tcmdb title|20167|Rainbow}}\n\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Judy Garland]]\n[[Category:1978 television films]]\n[[Category:1970s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:1970s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American musical drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Biographical television films]]\n[[Category:NBC network original films]]\n[[Category:Films based on biographies]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1920s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1930s]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about singers]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jackie Cooper]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rainbow_(1978_film)"}
{"title_page": "Rearts", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani music corporation}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Rearts\n| logo                = Rearts.png\n| image               = \n| image_caption       = \n| former_name         = \n| type                = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|2018|1}}\n| location            = [[Lahore]], [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n| key_people          = Najam Ul Assar <ref>http://startupguide.com.pk/najam-ul-assar-on-promoting-arts-through-technology/?fbclid=IwAR3pfpjp5C-Dq8lbIzu7aF3yDdr0VlvlGOVnQySW39fuEp-MaAXIQ00DDIA</ref> <br />(CEO)<br /> Azeem Hamid<br />(Creative Director)<br />Ahmad Butt<br />(Managing Director) <ref>https://dailytimes.com.pk/375222/shocking-video-of-female-hostess-has-gone-viral-on-social-media/</ref>\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| industry            = [[Music]]\n| products            = [[Music]]\n| revenue             = \n| net_income          = \n| num_employees       = \n| parent              = \n| divisions           = Rearts for Artists and Rearts Records\n| subsid              = \n| homepage            = [http://www.rearts.pk/ Official Website]\n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Rearts''' (Stylized and often referred to as rearts) is a Pakistani music distribution, record label and artist management company. It started in 2018 as a startup at the Plan 9 Incubator, a startup incubation program by the [[Punjab Information Technology Board]].<ref>https://plan9.pitb.gov.pk/cycle11</ref> It has two divisions, [[Rearts for Artists]], the artist representation and management division and [[Rearts Records]], a digital record label.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/reartspk/services|title=rearts|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nMany Pakistani musicians such as [[Kashmir - The Band|Kashmir]], [[Bayaan]] and [[Naseer & Shahab]] are signed with the company.\n\nThe company's office is located at Daftarkhwan Central- 90 B Hali Road, Block B, [[Gulberg, Lahore|Gulberg 2]] in [[Lahore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f6s.com/rearts|title=Rearts|website=F6S}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nRearts began as a startup at the [[Punjab Information Technology Board]]\u2019s Plan-9 Incubator startup program in [[Lahore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techjuice.pk/plan9-launchpad11-10-shortlisted-startups/|title=Plan9 Launchpad 11: Meet the 10 shortlisted startups|date=January 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Present==\n\nRearts presently has a number of artists signed up with them. The company is responsible for distributing and release of songs and albums and also has arranged musical events and concerts in [[Pakistan]].\n\nSongs and albums released under the Rearts Records banner are released digitally internationally on music streaming platforms such as [[Spotify]], [[YouTube]], [[Apple Music]], [[Amazon Music]], [[iTunes]], [[Deezer]], [[Google Play Music]], [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]], [[Saavn]], [[Genius (website)|Genius]] and [[Pandora Radio|Pandora]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ampl.ink/gyn9J|title=Naseer Afridi (Naseer & Shahab)|via=ampl.ink}}</ref>\n\nRearts has also organized many musical events in Pakistan ranging from album launches of its artists to music festivals. In 2019, the company organized a fundraising concert at the [[Alhamra Arts Council]] in [[Lahore]] featuring the musical acts [[Kashmir - The Band|Kashmir]], Badnaam and Bayaan to raise money for the eradication of [[Polio in Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.charcoalgravel.com/this-weekend-in-lahore-learning-and-yearning/|title=This Weekend in Lahore: Learning and Yearning|first=Purnea|last=Gillani|date=April 5, 2019}}</ref> Similarly, the previous year, it organized a motivational speaking event titled Failure Nights \u2013 Celebrating Failure which featured live music as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.propergaanda.com/failure-nights-celebrating-failures/|title=Failure Nights-Celebrating Failures|date=February 16, 2018}}</ref> Other events organized by Rearts include Rang-E-Kainat,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evensi.com/rang-kainat-musical-performance-harsukh-beaconhouse-newlands/256420590|title=Rang-e-Kainat - a musical performance by Harsukh - 12 May 2018|first=Rearts & Independent Theatre|last=Pakistan|website=Evensi}}</ref> Fashion Revolution Week, Face Music Mela <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/FACEinPakistan/posts/1871925982884878|title=FACE - Foundation for Arts, Culture & Education|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref> and the 2019 Mango Musik Festival in [[Islamabad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mangobaaz.com/edm-fans-in-islamabad-mango-musik-festival-in-islamabad-will-force-you-to-stay-up-late-very-very-late|title=EDM Fans In Islamabad, \"Mango\" Musik Festival In Islamabad Will Force To Stay Up Late. Very, Very Late.|first=Aam|last=Nawab|date=April 26, 2019|website=MangoBaaz}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Rearts provided the [[Laser harp]], the only one instrument available in Pakistan currently to be featured in Season 5 of the popular Pakistani music show [[Nescafe Basement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oyeyeah.com/entertainment/nescafe-basement-season-5-ends-on-a-powerful-note/|title=Nescafe Basement Season 5, ends on a powerful note|date=March 27, 2019|website=Oyeyeah}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1932555/4-nescafe-basement-closes-high-note-spreading-love-across-borders/|title=NESCAF\u00c9 Basement closes on high note with spreading love across borders|date=March 27, 2019|website=The Express Tribune}}</ref> The Laser Harp was featured in the song Resistance by 18 year old [[Lahore]] based [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] singer Abdullah Siddiqui and was played by Ahmad Butt who also serves as the managing director of Rearts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/magazine/instep-today/446927-nescafe-basement-5-blows-it-out-of-the-water-with-resistance|title=Nescafe Basement 5 blows it out of the water with \u2018Resistance\u2019|first=Maheen|last=Sabeeh|website=www.thenews.com.pk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/231704-abdullah-siddiqui-creating-shockwaves-with-his-edm-music-in-pakistan|title=Abdullah Siddiqui creating shockwaves with EDM in Pakistan &#124; Entertainment - Geo.tv|website=www.geo.tv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aurora.dawn.com/news/1143465|title=Nescaf\u00e9 Basement 5 \u2013 a season of diversity|first=Anusha|last=Zahid|date=May 29, 2019|website=Aurora Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1931789/4-18-year-old-bringing-electronic-dance-music-pakistan/|title=This 18-year-old is bringing Electronic Dance Music to Pakistan|date=March 18, 2019|website=The Express Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/04/opinion/nescafe-basement-delivers-top-season/|title=Asia Times &#124; \u2018Nescafe Basement\u2019 delivers top season &#124; Opinion|first=Asia|last=Times|website=Asia Times}}</ref>\n\nRearts has partnered with many Pakistani companies on different occasions such as Abacus Consulting, [[Beaconhouse School System]], [[Telenor Pakistan]] and [http://www.propergaanda.com/ ProperGaanda].\n\n==Services==\nRearts has two divisions working under it namely Rearts for Artists and Rearts Records.\n\n===Rearts for Artists===\n{{Infobox company\n|name= Rearts for Artists\n|type= [[Private company|Private]]\n|logo= \n|foundation= \n|location= [[Lahore]], [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n|key_people= \n|industry= [[Music]]\n|homepage= [http://www.rearts.com Rearts for Artists Official Website]\n}}\n\nRearts for Artists is the artist management division of Rearts. It is responsible for the management of artists under the company in different ways. It provides artists with services such as creating their portfolios, media solutions, legal representation, event management and public relations.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===Rearts Records===\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name = Rearts Records\n| image_name = Rearts Records logo.png\n| image_bg = \n| parent = Rearts\n| founded = {{start date and age|2018}}\n| founder = Rearts\n| status = Active\n| distributor = Rearts\n| genre = \n| country = [[Pakistan]] <!-- origin, such as \"[[Pakistan]]\" or \"{{Flag|Pakistan}}\" -->\n| location = [[Lahore]], [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n| url = [http://www.rearts.pk/ Official Website]\n}}\nRearts Records (Stylized as often referred to as rearts records) is the record label division of Rearts. It is responsible for the distribution and release of songs, EPs and albums of artists signed with the label to multiple international digital streaming platforms such as [[Spotify]], [[Saavn]], [[iTunes]], [[Apple Music]], [[Amazon Music]], [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]], [[Google Play Music]] and [[Deezer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Record-Label/reartsrecords/about/|title=rearts records|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nRearts Records is also responsible for music PR, design services as well as providing copyright and licensing support. It also organizes album launches and event tours for its artists.\n\n==Ukhano Controversy==\nOn 19th 2019, shortly after Pakistani vlogger Umer Khan better known as UKhano was accused of sexual harassment by multiple women, Naseer Afridi of [[Naseer & Shahab]] accused him of intellectual theft.<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/2016103/4-vlogger-ukano-responds-sexual-harassment-allegations/</ref> Khan had taken three of his songs namely Geet, Hero and Za Sta Pashan Nayam to CPIC, an investment company and claimed to have the rights. This was posted by Ahmad Butt, Rearts managing director on his [[Twitter]] as well as by Afridi on his [[Facebook]]. The company compensated Afridi for the use of his songs and Khan was heavily criticized on social media. The songs are released and distributed by Rearts worldwide on multiple music platforms.<ref>https://twitter.com/itsthepianoguy/status/1152184979474014209</ref><ref>https://www.mangobaaz.com/coke-studio-artist-naseer-afridi-is-claiming-that-ukhano-allegedly-stole-his-music</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fire Records (Pakistan)|Fire Records]]\n* [[Taazi]]\n* [[Patari (service)|Patari]]\n* [[Call (band)|Call]]\n* [[Zeb Bangash]]\n* [[Naseer & Shahab]]\n* [[Kashmir - The Band|Kashmir]]\n* ''[[Coke Studio (Pakistani TV program)|Coke Studio]]''\n* [[Nescafe Basement]]\n* [[Pepsi Battle of the Bands]]\n* [[Music of Pakistan]]\n* [[List of record labels]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://rearts.pk/ Rearts Official Website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/reartspk/ Rearts Official Facebook Page]\n* [https://twitter.com/reartspk/ Rearts Official Twitter Profile]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/reartspk/ Rearts Official Instagram Page]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC2cP84h1azrE_Y0YDbGHpcA/ Rearts Official YouTube Channel]\n* [http://rearts.pk/artists/ Rearts for Artists Official Website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/reartsrecords/ Rearts Records Official Facebook Page]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{Music digital distribution platforms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rearts}}\n[[Category:Pakistani record labels]]\n[[Category:Indie rock record labels]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock record labels]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Online music database clients]]\n[[Category:Online music stores of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Lahore]]\n[[Category:Punjab Information Technology Board]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani music corporation}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name = Rearts\n|logo = Rearts.png\n|image = \n|image_caption = \n|former_name = \n|type = [[Private company|Private]]\n|foundation = {{start date and age|2018|1}}\n|location = [[Lahore]], [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n|key_people = Najam Ul Asar<br />(CEO)<br /> Azeem Hamid<br />(Creative Director)<br />Ahmad Butt<br />(Managing Director) <ref>https://dailytimes.com.pk/375222/shocking-video-of-female-hostess-has-gone-viral-on-social-media/</ref>\n|area_served =Worldwide\n|industry = [[Music]]\n|products = [[Music]] \n|revenue = \n|net_income =\n|num_employees = \n|parent =\n|divisions = Rearts for Artists and Rearts Records\n|subsid = \n|homepage = [http://www.rearts.pk/ Official Website]\n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''Rearts''' (Stylized and often referred to as rearts) is a Pakistani music distribution, record label and artist management company. It started in 2018 as a startup at the Plan 9 Incubator, a startup incubation program by the [[Punjab Information Technology Board]].<ref>https://plan9.pitb.gov.pk/cycle11</ref> It has two divisions, [[Rearts for Artists]], the artist representation and management division and [[Rearts Records]], a digital record label.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/reartspk/services|title=rearts|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nMany Pakistani musicians such as [[Kashmir - The Band|Kashmir]], [[Bayaan]] and [[Naseer & Shahab]] are signed with the company.\n\nThe company's office is located at Daftarkhwan Central- 90 B Hali Road, Block B, [[Gulberg, Lahore|Gulberg 2]] in [[Lahore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f6s.com/rearts|title=Rearts|website=F6S}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nRearts began as a startup at the [[Punjab Information Technology Board]]\u2019s Plan-9 Incubator startup program in [[Lahore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techjuice.pk/plan9-launchpad11-10-shortlisted-startups/|title=Plan9 Launchpad 11: Meet the 10 shortlisted startups|date=January 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Present==\n\nRearts presently has a number of artists signed up with them. The company is responsible for distributing and release of songs and albums and also has arranged musical events and concerts in [[Pakistan]].\n\nSongs and albums released under the Rearts Records banner are released digitally internationally on music streaming platforms such as [[Spotify]], [[YouTube]], [[Apple Music]], [[Amazon Music]], [[iTunes]], [[Deezer]], [[Google Play Music]], [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]], [[Saavn]], [[Genius (website)|Genius]] and [[Pandora Radio|Pandora]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ampl.ink/gyn9J|title=Naseer Afridi (Naseer & Shahab)|via=ampl.ink}}</ref>\n\nRearts has also organized many musical events in Pakistan ranging from album launches of its artists to music festivals. In 2019, the company organized a fundraising concert at the [[Alhamra Arts Council]] in [[Lahore]] featuring the musical acts [[Kashmir - The Band|Kashmir]], Badnaam and Bayaan to raise money for the eradication of [[Polio in Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.charcoalgravel.com/this-weekend-in-lahore-learning-and-yearning/|title=This Weekend in Lahore: Learning and Yearning|first=Purnea|last=Gillani|date=April 5, 2019}}</ref> Similarly, the previous year, it organized a motivational speaking event titled Failure Nights \u2013 Celebrating Failure which featured live music as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.propergaanda.com/failure-nights-celebrating-failures/|title=Failure Nights-Celebrating Failures|date=February 16, 2018}}</ref> Other events organized by Rearts include Rang-E-Kainat,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evensi.com/rang-kainat-musical-performance-harsukh-beaconhouse-newlands/256420590|title=Rang-e-Kainat - a musical performance by Harsukh - 12 May 2018|first=Rearts & Independent Theatre|last=Pakistan|website=Evensi}}</ref> Fashion Revolution Week, Face Music Mela <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/FACEinPakistan/posts/1871925982884878|title=FACE - Foundation for Arts, Culture & Education|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref> and the 2019 Mango Musik Festival in [[Islamabad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mangobaaz.com/edm-fans-in-islamabad-mango-musik-festival-in-islamabad-will-force-you-to-stay-up-late-very-very-late|title=EDM Fans In Islamabad, \"Mango\" Musik Festival In Islamabad Will Force To Stay Up Late. Very, Very Late.|first=Aam|last=Nawab|date=April 26, 2019|website=MangoBaaz}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Rearts provided the [[Laser harp]], the only one instrument available in Pakistan currently to be featured in Season 5 of the popular Pakistani music show [[Nescafe Basement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oyeyeah.com/entertainment/nescafe-basement-season-5-ends-on-a-powerful-note/|title=Nescafe Basement Season 5, ends on a powerful note|date=March 27, 2019|website=Oyeyeah}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1932555/4-nescafe-basement-closes-high-note-spreading-love-across-borders/|title=NESCAF\u00c9 Basement closes on high note with spreading love across borders|date=March 27, 2019|website=The Express Tribune}}</ref> The Laser Harp was featured in the song Resistance by 18 year old [[Lahore]] based [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] singer Abdullah Siddiqui and was played by Ahmad Butt who also serves as the managing director of Rearts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/magazine/instep-today/446927-nescafe-basement-5-blows-it-out-of-the-water-with-resistance|title=Nescafe Basement 5 blows it out of the water with \u2018Resistance\u2019|first=Maheen|last=Sabeeh|website=www.thenews.com.pk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/231704-abdullah-siddiqui-creating-shockwaves-with-his-edm-music-in-pakistan|title=Abdullah Siddiqui creating shockwaves with EDM in Pakistan &#124; Entertainment - Geo.tv|website=www.geo.tv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aurora.dawn.com/news/1143465|title=Nescaf\u00e9 Basement 5 \u2013 a season of diversity|first=Anusha|last=Zahid|date=May 29, 2019|website=Aurora Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1931789/4-18-year-old-bringing-electronic-dance-music-pakistan/|title=This 18-year-old is bringing Electronic Dance Music to Pakistan|date=March 18, 2019|website=The Express Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/04/opinion/nescafe-basement-delivers-top-season/|title=Asia Times &#124; \u2018Nescafe Basement\u2019 delivers top season &#124; Opinion|first=Asia|last=Times|website=Asia Times}}</ref>\n\nRearts has partnered with many Pakistani companies on different occasions such as Abacus Consulting, [[Beaconhouse School System]], [[Telenor Pakistan]] and [http://www.propergaanda.com/ ProperGaanda].\n\n==Services==\nRearts has two divisions working under it namely Rearts for Artists and Rearts Records.\n\n===Rearts for Artists===\n{{Infobox company\n|name= Rearts for Artists\n|type= [[Private company|Private]]\n|logo= \n|foundation= \n|location= [[Lahore]], [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n|key_people= \n|industry= [[Music]]\n|homepage= [http://www.rearts.com Rearts for Artists Official Website]\n}}\n\nRearts for Artists is the artist management division of Rearts. It is responsible for the management of artists under the company in different ways. It provides artists with services such as creating their portfolios, media solutions, legal representation, event management and public relations.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===Rearts Records===\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name = Rearts Records\n| image_name = Rearts Records logo.png\n| image_bg = \n| parent = Rearts\n| founded = {{start date and age|2018}}\n| founder = Rearts\n| status = Active\n| distributor = Rearts\n| genre = \n| country = [[Pakistan]] <!-- origin, such as \"[[Pakistan]]\" or \"{{Flag|Pakistan}}\" -->\n| location = [[Lahore]], [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n| url = [http://www.rearts.pk/ Official Website]\n}}\nRearts Records (Stylized as often referred to as rearts records) is the record label division of Rearts. It is responsible for the distribution and release of songs, EPs and albums of artists signed with the label to multiple international digital streaming platforms such as [[Spotify]], [[Saavn]], [[iTunes]], [[Apple Music]], [[Amazon Music]], [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]], [[Google Play Music]] and [[Deezer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Record-Label/reartsrecords/about/|title=rearts records|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nRearts Records is also responsible for music PR, design services as well as providing copyright and licensing support. It also organizes album launches and event tours for its artists.\n\n==Ukhano Controversy==\nOn 19th 2019, shortly after Pakistani vlogger Umer Khan better known as UKhano was accused of sexual harassment by multiple women, Naseer Afridi of [[Naseer & Shahab]] accused him of intellectual theft.<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/2016103/4-vlogger-ukano-responds-sexual-harassment-allegations/</ref> Khan had taken three of his songs namely Geet, Hero and Za Sta Pashan Nayam to CPIC, an investment company and claimed to have the rights. This was posted by Ahmad Butt, Rearts managing director on his [[Twitter]] as well as by Afridi on his [[Facebook]]. The company compensated Afridi for the use of his songs and Khan was heavily criticized on social media. The songs are released and distributed by Rearts worldwide on multiple music platforms.<ref>https://twitter.com/itsthepianoguy/status/1152184979474014209</ref><ref>https://www.mangobaaz.com/coke-studio-artist-naseer-afridi-is-claiming-that-ukhano-allegedly-stole-his-music</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fire Records (Pakistan)|Fire Records]]\n* [[Taazi]]\n* [[Patari (service)|Patari]]\n* [[Call (band)|Call]]\n* [[Zeb Bangash]]\n* [[Naseer & Shahab]]\n* [[Kashmir - The Band|Kashmir]]\n* ''[[Coke Studio (Pakistani TV program)|Coke Studio]]''\n* [[Nescafe Basement]]\n* [[Pepsi Battle of the Bands]]\n* [[Music of Pakistan]]\n* [[List of record labels]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://rearts.pk/ Rearts Official Website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/reartspk/ Rearts Official Facebook Page]\n* [https://twitter.com/reartspk/ Rearts Official Twitter Profile]\